  <data name="en_pano45_description"><![CDATA[The warriors or raiders would line up the people that they captured just like prisoners of war and lead the captives to quarters of slave holders and merchants. Sometimes, the same warriors or recruiters helped to escort slaves from quarters to the many slave markets in the hinterland. Legend records that the slave traders did most of their long distance traveling to markets close to the coastal towns at night or through forest trails during the day. Among the escorts were medicine men or herbalists who provided treatments to slaves who fell sick.]]></data>



  <data name="en_pano46_description"><![CDATA[<div>This is one of the slave cells, it was built by slave merchants in Bende (Local Government Area of Abia state.), which was one of the most active slave markets in the nineteenth century. This building served as a holding place for slaves ready to be sold.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>Slave raiders and recruiters were mainly warriors from a number of villages.</div>]]></data>



  <data name="en_pano47_description"><![CDATA[<div>This is the slave market, at the center of the market is an Achi tree, its surface roots measured 25 feet, When slaves were captured, they were tied to the root of this massive tree and before being taken away they were made to seat on stones called “stones of disorientation” as a way to deter them from running away from their masters.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>This tree and the stones are shrine objects and legend has it that when a slaves sits on the stones they would lose their sense of direction thus they would not find their way back to their homes or they cannot escape from their masters.</div>]]></data>


